article.headline: Jackson scores 21 in matchup of WNBA champions
article.linkText: Storm's Jackson overcomes bum ankle and Shock
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson ignored her ankle pain and led the
Seattle Storm to victory.

Jackson scored 21 points four days after spraining her right
ankle, while Sue Bird added 14 and Betty Lennox had 10, guiding
Seattle to a 74-71 win Saturday over the Detroit Shock in a meeting
between the last two WNBA champions.

"That kid is in quite a bit of pain," Storm coach Anne Donovan
said. "Certain plays of the game, you could really see where she
was trying to fight through it. ... She really had to play strong
mentally to get through it today."

Jackson started but wore a brace, which she'll probably use for
the rest of the season. It's the same ankle the former MVP had
surgically repaired before the season.

"It's fine. It's not comfortable, no, but it's not going to
stop me from playing," said Jackson, who made 10-of-11 free throws
and logged 37 minutes.

Donovan had hoped to give her star player more time on the
bench, but it wasn't possible because Janelle Burse battled foul
trouble and Suzy Batkovic was inconsistent in the first half.

Not that it bothered Jackson.

"Not at all. I knew this was going to be a huge game for us,"
she said. "I knew the Shock were going to try and come out to kill
us on television. I didn't expect that I'd be playing any less
minutes."

The Storm couldn't protect a 24-12 lead midway through the first
half and survived a 38-28 rebounding deficit, using a 7-0 scoring
run late in the second half to build a 67-63 lead with 4:19 to
play.

It was just enough of a margin for Seattle to win its fourth
straight.

The Storm (12-10) also forced a logjam atop the Western
Conference standings, where four teams -- Seattle, Houston, Los
Angeles and Minnesota -- are within two games of first-place
Sacramento.

"We're starting to play good basketball at the right time,"
Donovan said. "In the West, it's nobody's game. We're still after
a playoff spot, obviously, but we're also after homecourt advantage
as well."

Deanna Nolan scored 22 points for Detroit (8-11) , which has won
only twice in its last 12 games. Cheryl Ford added 15 points and 16
rebounds. Chandi Jones scored 10 as a reserve, all in the first
half.

"We're losing the close ones," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer
said. "That's four close ones in a row that we haven't been able
to find a way to win. It's the little things that are costing us."

Seattle led 71-66 after two free throws by Jackson with 1:37
remaining, but Nolan made two free throws and added a jumper from
just inside the 3-point line to pull the Shock within 71-70 with
1:01 left.

Ruth Riley made one of two free throw attempts, tying it with 39
seconds to go.

Lennox swished a baseline jumper off an inbounds play -- with
Jackson clearing space on a screen -- to put Seattle ahead 73-71
with 18.1 seconds remaining. The Shock used a timeout to set up a
play, but Nolan missed a 3-point try with 7 seconds to play.

"We really stayed together down the stretch," said Lennox, the
MVP of last year's WNBA Finals. "We stayed focused and we stayed
together as a team. That was the biggest difference."

Lennox added a free throw to make it 74-71, leaving the Shock
4.2 seconds for a chance to force overtime. But the best shot
Detroit could get was Nolan's one-armed throw from deep in the
backcourt just before the horn.

"That wasn't the play, but it kind of broke down so they left
me open for a three," Nolan said.

In a tightly officiated contest that left both benches
complaining regularly about calls, the Shock were whistled for 29
fouls to the Storm's 24.

Nolan scored 10 points in the final 4 minutes before halftime,
helping the Shock erase a 24-12 deficit and force a 44-44 tie at
the break. Detroit missed only two of its final 15 field goal
attempts in the first half.

"We're playing hard right now," Nolan said. "It's just that
we're having a hard time pulling them out."
